rative disorders", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9339234232902527, "span": {"begin": 984, "end": 1011}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7124"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TNF", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9851352572441101, "span": {"begin": 1073, "end": 1076}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4781"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NF-B", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9459961652755737, "span": {"begin": 1107, "end": 1111}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5599"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "JNK", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9853274822235107, "span": {"begin": 1116, "end": 1119}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4217"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "apoptosis signal-regulating kinase 1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9765955209732056, "span": {"begin": 1293, "end": 1329}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4217"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ASK1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9918400049209595, "span": {"begin": 1331, "end": 1335}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:65268"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "MAP kinase kinase kinase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9954976439476013, "span": {"begin": 1364, "end": 1388}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4216"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MAPKKK", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9968931674957275, "span": {"begin": 1390, "end": 1396}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5599"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "JNK", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9942014813423157, "span": {"begin": 1414, "end": 1417}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5594"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "p38", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8857806921005249, "span": {"begin": 1422, "end": 1425}}], "text": "Reactive oxygen species (ROS) can be derived from exogenous sources or produced in vivo; these include the superoxide anion (O 2), the hydroxyl radical (OH), and hydrogen&nbsp; peroxide (H 2O2). ROS at low levels participate in cell signaling while higher ROS concentrations are deleterious due to the oxidation of proteins, lipids, and DNA. Additionally,&nbsp; persistent ROS production compromises the cellular antioxidant defense systems and results in oxidative stress and apoptosis (337). ROS can initiate apoptosis via the&nbsp; mitochondrial and death receptor pathways. In the former, ROS have been shown to induce loss of the m, release of mitochondrial pro-apoptotic proteins, and activation of caspase 3 (49).  ROS signaling has been shown to mediate cytokine-induced apoptosis&nbsp;(Okouchi et al., 2007). TNF is a pro-inflammatory cytokine produced by macrophages and is the most studied cytokine in&nbsp; apoptosis and the pathophysiology of various diseases, including neurodegenerative disorders&nbsp;(Jackson et al., 1999). Mechanistically, the binding of TNF to its receptor activates the NF-B and JNK signaling pathways believed to be mediated by ROS&nbsp;(Okouchi et al., 2007).&nbsp; A role for ROS has also been implicated in death receptor-mediated apoptosis induced by apoptosis signal-regulating kinase 1 (ASK1), an ubquitiously expressed MAP kinase kinase kinase (MAPKKK), that activates JNK and p38 MAP kinase pathways&nbsp;(Okouchi et al., 2007).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:07:26 +0000 2026"}